    "body": "## Problem\n\nNo ergonomic way to \"reset\" Nvim's internal and public state. \n\n\n\n## Expected behavior\n\nIntroduce a best-effort/experimental `nvim__reset` API. Initially it might only clear low-hanging-fruit such as:\n\n- options (`:set all&`)\n- `vim.loader`\n- script cache\n- Vimscript globals `vim.g`\n- Lua globals\n- timers\n\nMore \"advanced\" stuff that could potentially follow (again, on a \"use at your own risk basis\"):\n\n- libuv handles, file descriptors, streams\n- internal state such as `early_init`, and other very low-level initializers\n\n### Benefits:\n\n- Performance: Useful [in tests](https://github.com/neovim/pynvim/issues/601#issuecomment-3323186193), to avoid re-spawning `nvim` (~30ms time cost, although https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/34820 will avoid it (but that doesn't help third-party consumers)).\n- Architecture: even if it's not \"perfect\", having a \"best effort\" way to clear \"most of\" the state is a valuable exercise because it (1) centralizes all the \"global state\" concepts in one place, and (2) drives us to mature the \"context\" and \"shada\" concepts.",
